atus and vital signs are carefully monitored.', 'Others', 'Naltrexone, Naloxone, Oxycodone, Acetaminophen, Ibuprofen, Celecoxib, Codeine, Acetylsalicylic acid, Buprenorphine, Nalbuphine', 'Amantadine', 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/109085/', '[1] "Product Information. Eldepryl (selegiline)." Somerset Pharmaceuticals Inc, Tampa, FL.[2] Sternbach H "The serotonin syndrome." Am J Psychiatry 148 (1991): 705-13[3] "Product Information. Furoxone (furazolidone)." Roberts Pharmaceutical Corporation, Eatontown, NJ.[4] Garbutt JC "Potentiation of propoxyphene by phenelzine." Am J Psychiatry 144 (1987): 251-2[5] Starr C "Interaction between pethidine and selegiline." Lancet 337 (1991): 554[6] Gillman PK "Possible serotonin syndrome with moclobemide and pethidine." Med J Aust 162 (1995): 554[7] Zornberg GL, Hegarty JD "Adverse interaction between propoxyphene and phenelzine." Am J Psychiatry 150 (1993): 1270-1[8] Nierenberg DW, Semprebon M "The central nervous system serotonin syndrome." Clin Pharmacol Ther 53 (1993): 84-8[9] "Product Information. Demerol (meperidine)." Sanofi Winthrop Pharmaceuticals, New York, NY.[10] Weiner AL "Meperidine as a potential cause of serotonin syndrome in the emergency department." Acad Emerg Med 6 (1999): 156-8[11] Martin TG "Serotonin syndrome." Ann Emerg Med 28 (1996): 520-6[12] Schulz R, Antonin KH, Hoffmann E, et al "Tyramine kinetics and pressor sensitivity during monoamine oxidase inhibition by selegiline." Clin Pharmacol Ther 46 (1989): 528-36[13] Pettinger WA, Soyangco FG, Oates JA "Inhibition of monoamine oxidase in man by furazolidone." Clin Pharmacol Ther 9 (1968): 442-7[14] Youssef MS, Wilkinson PA "Epidural fentanyl and monoamine oxidase inhibitors." Anaesthesia 43 (1988): 210-2[15] De Vita VT, Hahn MA, Oliverio VT "Monoamine oxidase inhibition by a new carcinostatic agent, n-isopropyl-a-(2-methylhydrazino)-p-toluamide (MIH). (30590)." Proc Soc Exp Biol Med 120 (1965):