hine may also have significant CNS interactions with MAOIs, it is generally considered a safer alternative in patients treated with MAOIs who require a narcotic analgesic.', 'Others', 'Naloxone, Naltrexone, Celecoxib', 'Amantadine', 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/109090/', '[1] Zornberg GL, Hegarty JD "Adverse interaction between propoxyphene and phenelzine." Am J Psychiatry 150 (1993): 1270-1[2] Gillman PK "Possible serotonin syndrome with moclobemide and pethidine." Med J Aust 162 (1995): 554[3] "Product Information. Azilect (rasagiline)." Teva Pharmaceuticals USA, North Wales, PA.[4] "Product Information. Furoxone (furazolidone)." Roberts Pharmaceutical Corporation, Eatontown, NJ.[5] "Product Information. Demerol (meperidine)." Sanofi Winthrop Pharmaceuticals, New York, NY.[6] Upton R, Graff A, Williamson E, et al. "American Herbal Pharmacopoeia and Therapeutic Compendium. Monograph printed in Herbalgram." Herbalgram 40 (1997): 1-38(monograph)[7] Hardman JG, Gilman AG, Limbird LE eds. "Goodman and Gilman''s the Pharmacological Basis of Therapeutics. 9th ed." New York, NY: McGraw-Hill (1995):[8] Das PK, Warkentin DI, Hewko R, Forrest DL "Serotonin syndrome after concomitant treatment with linezolid and meperidine." Clin Infect Dis 46 (2008): 264-5[9] "Product Information. Nardil (phenelzine)." Parke-Dvis, Morris Plains, NJ.[10] De Vita VT, Hahn MA, Oliverio VT "Monoamine oxidase inhibition by a new carcinostatic agent, n-isopropyl-a-(2-methylhydrazino)-p-toluamide (MIH). (30590)." Proc Soc Exp Biol Med 120 (1965): 561-5[11] Martin TG "Serotonin syndrome." Ann Emerg Med 28 (1996): 520-6[12] Evans-Prosser CD "The use of pethidine and morphine in the presence of monoamine oxidase inhibitors." Br J Anaesth 40 (1968): 279-82[13] Pettinger WA, Soyangco FG, Oates JA "Inhibition of monoamine oxidase in man by furazolidone." Clin Pharmacol Ther 9 (1968): 442-7[14] Goldberg LI "Monoamine oxidase inhibitors: adv